Content:
Kotlin has a notion of function inlining with the return statement being inlined too. This means you can do, e.g.:<p>list.forEach {
  if (it == something) return;
}<p>and you aren&#x27;t returning from the code block, but the enclosing function. Yet behind the scenes forEach is being expanded by the compiler into a regular imperative for loop, in a macro-like way.
